Proof.
Empirically, estimates of range from 0.47 to 0.65 depending on the survey instrument: Consumer Expenditure Survey (CES) methods yield approximately 47–50%, while approaches reconciled with the Survey of Consumer Finances (SCF) and national accounts yield approximately 59–65% (Moody’s Analytics, 2023). We use as a central estimate, following Moody’s Analytics (2023), but conduct sensitivity analysis across the full range. A 10% income reduction for the top quintile () produces an aggregate consumption decline of 4.7–6.5% depending on —spanning the range of consumption collapse observed during the 2008–2009 Global Financial Crisis.
